**Observations**

The dataset presents a substantial sparsity challenge at 98.30%, meaning that out of all possible user–movie interactions only 1.70% carry an actual rating. This extreme sparsity is the single most important factor shaping how each similarity metric performs, and it explains the dramatic gap between methods that handle missing data gracefully and those that do not.

Cosine Similarity emerged as the clear winner with an RMSE of 0.8520 and an MAE of 0.6522, meaning that on average the model's predictions deviate from the true rating by roughly two-thirds of a star. This is a strong result for a memory-based collaborative filtering approach operating on such a sparse matrix. Cosine works well here because it naturally handles the zero-filled entries as neutral — two items that share even a small set of co-rated users will still produce a meaningful similarity score, and the zeros in unrated positions do not distort the angle between vectors as aggressively as mean-subtracted zeros would.

Pearson Correlation came in a close second with an RMSE of 0.8644 and MAE of 0.6632, trailing Cosine by only about 1.5%. The small gap makes sense because Pearson is mathematically equivalent to cosine similarity after centering each item by its own column mean. On a matrix dominated by zeros, this centering shifts the "baseline" only slightly, so the resulting similarity structure stays largely aligned with raw cosine. The marginal loss in accuracy suggests that item-mean centering introduces a small amount of noise when most entries are zero, but the effect is minor.

Adjusted Cosine performed significantly worse than the other two methods, posting an RMSE of 2.3678 and MAE of 2.0666 — nearly three times the error of Cosine. This poor performance is directly attributable to the sparsity problem. Adjusted Cosine subtracts each user's mean rating before computing similarity, which is theoretically sound because it normalises for the fact that some users are generous raters while others are strict. However, when 98.3% of the matrix entries are missing and filled with zero, subtracting the user mean from rated entries while leaving unrated entries at zero creates vectors where the vast majority of dimensions carry an artificial negative signal (0 minus a positive mean). This noise overwhelms the genuine rating information and produces similarity estimates that are unreliable for prediction.

All three methods achieved nearly identical coverage, ranging from 96.2% to 96.3%, which means the model was able to generate a prediction for roughly 1,924 out of 2,000 test samples regardless of the similarity metric used. The ~4% of unpredictable cases correspond to movies or users that appear in the test set but have no representation in the training matrix. This confirms that the performance differences are purely about prediction quality rather than the ability to produce predictions at all.

The similarity heatmap for the top-10 most popular movies reveals intuitive genre-based clustering. The 90s drama trio of Forrest Gump, Shawshank Redemption, and Pulp Fiction form the tightest cluster with pairwise similarities around 0.58, reflecting a strong overlap in the audiences that rate these films. Action-adventure titles like Jurassic Park, Terminator 2, and Braveheart form their own neighbourhood with similarities between 0.56 and 0.60. The Matrix and Star Wars act as bridge nodes with moderate connections to both clusters, which aligns with their cross-genre appeal. Toy Story stands out as the most dissimilar movie in the top 10, with its highest similarity to any other title reaching only 0.46, consistent with its unique position as the only animated family film in a group of adult-oriented titles.

The top-10 recommendations for User 1 show several entries with a perfect predicted score of 5.0, which is common in item-based CF when the user's rated neighbours are few but highly similar and all carry maximum ratings. This suggests that incorporating a confidence penalty — for example weighting predictions lower when they are based on very few neighbours — could produce a more nuanced and trustworthy ranking in practice.
